solution.p:
The equation x^4 = 4 has an isolated integer power on the left. The inverse operation is a fourth root. Because the power is even, there are two solutions.
x^4=4 \sqrt[4]{x^4} = \sqrt[4]{4} x = \pm \sqrt[4]{4}
Because 4=2^2, we could rewrite this as x = \pm(2^2)^{\frac{1}{4}} = \pm 2^{\frac{2}{4}} = \pm 2^{\frac{1}{2}} = \pm \sqrt{2}.

We find the inverse function (the reverse projection function) by solving the recurrent relation for P_n.

  P_{n} = 1.5 P_{n-1} - 100
  P_{n} + 100 = 1.5 P_{n-1} = \frac{3}{2} P_{n-1}
  \frac{2}{3}(P_{n} + 100) = P_{n-1}

Consequently, the inverse projection function is f^{-1}(x) = \frac{2}{3}(x+100).

With the inverse projection function, we can work the sequence backwards from the initial value. Starting with P_0 = 5000, we find
P_{-1} = f^{-1}(5000) = \frac{2}{3}(5000+100) = 3400 P_{-2} = f^{-1}(3400) = \frac{2}{3}(3400+100) = \frac{7000}{3}
The exact value from our model is P_{-2} \approx 2333\frac{1}{3}. Even though a population has integer values and this prediction is definitely not an integer, we would report our model value unless we had information on how many significant digits to keep.
